<em>Philosophical Studies</em>, 172(5): 1127&ndash;1142.
doi:10.1007/s11098-014-0340-x</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2016, &ldquo;Teleology and
Normativity&rdquo;, <em>Oxford Studies in Metaethics</em>, 11:
214&ndash;240.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, &ldquo;Review of Andreas M&uuml;ller,
<em>Constructing Practical Reasons</em>&rdquo;, <em>Mind</em>,
131(526): 531&ndash;539. doi: 10.1093/mind/fzab041</li>

<li>Singh, Keshav, 2022, &ldquo;What&rsquo;s in an Aim?&rdquo;,
<em>Oxford Studies in Metaethics</em>, 17: 138&ndash;165.</li>

<li>Smit, Houston, 2003, &ldquo;Internalism and the Origins of
Rational Motivation&rdquo;, <em>Journal of Ethics</em>, 7(2):
183&ndash;231. doi:10.1023/A:1022950720463</li>

<li>Smith, Michael, 1994, <em>The Moral Problem</em>, Oxford:
Blackwell.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1999, &ldquo;The Search for the
Source&rdquo;, <em>The Philosophical Quarterly</em>, 49(196):
384&ndash;394. doi:10.1111/1467-9213.00150</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2012, &ldquo;Agents and Patients, or: What
We Learn About Reasons for Action by Reflecting on Our Choices in
Process-of-Thought Cases&rdquo;, <em>Proceedings of the Aristotelian
Society</em>, 112(3): 309&ndash;331.
doi:10.1111/j.1467-9264.2012.00337.x</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2013, &ldquo;A Constitutivist Theory of
Reasons: Its Promise and Parts&rdquo;, <em>Law, Ethics, and
Philosophy</em>, 1: 9&ndash;30.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2015, &ldquo;The Magic of
Constitutivism&rdquo;, <em>American Philosophical Quarterly</em>,
52(2): 187&ndash;200.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2017, &ldquo;Constitutivism&rdquo;, in
<em>The Routledge Handbook of Metaethics</em>, Colin McPherson and
David Plunkett (eds.), New York: Routledge, pp. 371&ndash;384.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2018a, &ldquo;Three Kinds of Moral
Rationalism&rdquo; in Karen Jones and Francois Schroeter (eds.),
<em>The Many Moral Rationalisms</em>, Oxford: Oxford University Press,
pp. 48&ndash;69.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2018b, &ldquo;Constitutivism&rdquo; in
<em>Routledge Handbook of Metaethics</em>, Tristram McPherson and
David Plunkett (eds.), London: Routledge, pp. 371&ndash;384.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2020, &ldquo;The Modal Conception of Ideal
Rational Agents: Objectively Ideal Not Merely Subjective Ideal,
Advisors not Exemplars, Agentially Concerned Not Agentially
Indifferent, Social Not Solitary, Self-and-Other Regarding, Not Wholly
Self-Regarding&rdquo;, in <em>Explorations in Ethics</em>, David
Kaspar (ed.), Palgrave-Macmillan, pp. 59&ndash;79.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2023, &ldquo;The Bearing of Moral
Rationalism&rdquo;, in <em>Oxford Handbook of Moral Realism</em>, Paul
Bloomfield and David Copp (eds.), New York: Oxford University Press,
pp. 84&ndash;105.</li>

<li>Stein, Sebastian, 2020, &ldquo;Choosing to Do the Right Thing:
Aristotle, Kant, and Hegel on Practical Normativity and the
Realism-Constructivism Debate&rdquo;, in Gledhill and Stein 2020, pp.
50&ndash;87.</li>

<li>Stern, Robert, 2007, &ldquo;Freedom, Self-Legislation and Morality
in Kant and Hegel: Constructivist vs. Realist Accounts&rdquo;, in
Espen Hammer (ed.), <em>German Idealism: Contemporary
Perspectives</em>, Abingdon: Routledge, pp. 245&ndash;66.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2000, <em>Transcendental Arguments:
Answering the Question of Justification</em>, Oxford: Oxford
University Press.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2012a, <em>Understanding Moral
Obligation</em>, Cambridge: Cambridge University Press.
doi:10.1017/CBO9780511997747</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2012b, &ldquo;Constructivism and the
Argument from Autonomy&rdquo;, in Lenman and Shemmer 2012a:
119&ndash;137. doi:10.1093/acprof:oso/9780199609833.003.0007</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2013, &ldquo;Moral Scepticism,
Constructivism and the Value of Humanity&rdquo;, in Bagnoli (ed.)
2013a, pp. 22&ndash;40. doi:10.1017/CBO9781139094221.003</li>

<li>Stieb, James A., 2006, &ldquo;Moral Realism and Kantian
Constructivism&rdquo;, <em>Ratio Juris</em>, 19(4): 402&ndash;20.
doi:10.1111/j.1467-9337.2006.00335.x</li>

<li>Street, Sharon, 2006, &ldquo;A Darwinian Dilemma for Realist
Theories of Value&rdquo;, <em>Philosophical Studies</em>, 127(1):
109&ndash;166. doi:10.1007/s11098-005-1726-6</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2008a, &ldquo;Constructivism about
Reasons&rdquo;, <em>Oxford Studies in Metaethics</em>, 3:
208&ndash;245.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2008b, &ldquo;Reply to Copp: Naturalism,
Normativity, and the Varieties of Realism worth Worrying About&rdquo;,
<em>Philosophical Issues</em>, 18(1): 207&ndash;228.
doi:10.1111/j.1533-6077.2008.00145.x</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2009, &ldquo;In Defense of Future Tuesday
Indifference: Ideally Coherent Eccentrics and the Contingency of What
Matters&rdquo;, <em>Philosophical Issues</em>, 19(1): 273&ndash;298.
doi:10.1111/j.1533-6077.2009.00170.x</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2010, &ldquo;What is Constructivism in
Ethics and Metaethics?&rdquo;, <em>Philosophy Compass</em>, 5(5):
363&ndash;384. doi:10.1111/j.1747-9991.2009.00280.x</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2011, &ldquo;Mind-Independence Without the
Mystery: Why Quasi-Realists Can&rsquo;t Have it Both Ways&rdquo;,
<em>Oxford Studies in Metaethics</em>, 6: 1&ndash;32.
doi:10.1093/acprof:oso/9780199606375.003.0001</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2012, &ldquo;Coming to Terms with
Contingency: Humean Constructivism about Practical Reason&rdquo;,
Lenman and Shemmer 2012a, pp. 40&ndash;59.
doi:10.1093/acprof:oso/9780199609833.003.0003</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2016a, &ldquo;Constructivism in Ethics and
the Problem of Attachment and Loss&rdquo;, <em>Proceedings of the
Aristotelian Society</em> (Supplementary Volume), 90(1):
161&ndash;189.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2016b, &ldquo;Objectivity and Truth:
You&rsquo;d Better Rethink It&rdquo;, <em>Oxford Studies in
Metaethics</em>, 11: 293&ndash;334.
doi:10.1093/acprof:oso/9780198784647.003.0012</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2017, &ldquo;Nothing &lsquo;Really&rsquo;
Matters, but That&rsquo;s Not What Matters&rdquo;, in <em>Does
Anything Really Matter: Parfit on Objectivity</em>, Peter Singer
(ed.), Oxford: Oxford University Press, pp. 121&ndash;148.</li>

<li>Stueber, Karsten R, 2017, &ldquo;Smithian Constructivism:
Elucidating the Reality of the Normative Domain&rdquo;, in Karsten R.
Stueber and Remy Debes (eds.), <em>Ethical Sentimentalism: New
Perspectives</em>, Cambridge University Press, pp. 171&ndash;91.</li>

<li>Suther, Jensen, 2020, &ldquo;Hegel&rsquo;s Logic of Freedom:
Toward a &lsquo;Logical Constitutivism&rsquo;&rdquo;, <em>Review of
Metaphysics</em>, 73(4): 771&ndash;814.</li>

<li>Tenenbaum, Sergio, 2019, &ldquo;Formalism and Constitutivism in
Kantian Practical Philosophy&rdquo;, <em>Philosophical
Explorations</em>, 22(2): 163&ndash;176.
doi:10.1080/13869795.2019.1599053</li>

<li>Thompson, Michael J., 2020, &ldquo;Critical Agency in Hegelian
Ethics: Social Metaphysics versus Moral Constructivism&rdquo;, in
Gledhill and Stein 2020, pp. 256&ndash;287.</li>

<li>Thorpe, Lucas, 2019, &ldquo;What&rsquo;s wrong with Constructivist
Readings of Kant?&rdquo;, in <em>The Philosophy of Kant</em>, Ricardo
Gutierrez Aguilar (ed.), New York: Nova Science Publishers, pp.
165&ndash;186.</li>

<li>Tiberius, Valerie, 2012, &ldquo;Constructivism and Wise
Judgment&rdquo;, in Lenman and Shemmer 2012a, pp. 195&ndash;212.
doi:10.1093/acprof:oso/9780199609833.003.0011</li>

<li>Tiffany, Evan, 2006, &ldquo;How Kantian Must Kantian
Constructivists Be?&rdquo;, <em>Inquiry</em>, 49(6): 524&ndash;46.
doi:10.1080/00201740601016205</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2012, &ldquo;Why Be an Agent?&rdquo;,
<em>Australasian Journal of Philosophy</em>, 90(2): 223&ndash;233.
doi:10.1080/00048402.2011.605792</li>

<li>Timmons, Mark, 2003, &ldquo;The Limits of Moral
Constructivism&rdquo;, <em>Ratio</em>, 16(4): 391&ndash;423.
doi:10.1046/j.1467- 9329.2003.00230.x</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2017, <em>Significance and System: Essays
on Kant&rsquo;s Ethics</em>, New York: Oxford University Press.</li>

<li>Timmons, Mark and Sorin Baiasu (eds.), 2013, <em>Kant on Practical
Justification: Interpretive Essays</em>, Oxford: Oxford University
Press. doi:10.1093/acprof:oso/9780195395686.001.0001</li>

<li>Tropman, Elizabeth, 2014, &ldquo;Evolutionary Debunking Arguments:
Moral Realism, Constructivism, and Explaining Moral Knowledge&rdquo;,
<em>Philosophical Explorations</em>, 17(2): 126&ndash;140.</li>

<li>Tubert, Ariela, 2010, &ldquo;Constitutive Arguments&rdquo;,
<em>Philosophy Compass</em>, 5(8): 656&ndash;666.</li>

<li>Turan, Caner. 2019. &ldquo;Necessary Constructivism in
Kant&rsquo;s Moral Theory&rdquo;, in <em>The Philosophy of Kant</em>,
R. G. Aguilar (ed.), Nova Science Publishers, pp. 187&ndash;212.</li>

<li>Velleman, J. David, 2009, <em>How We Get Along</em>, Cambridge:
Cambridge University Press. doi:10.1017/CBO9780511808296</li>

<li>Vesper, Achim, 2020, &ldquo;Virtues and Vices of Kantian
Constructivism&rdquo;, <em>Studi Kantiani</em>, 33:
169&ndash;177.</li>

<li>Walden, Kenneth, 2012, &ldquo;Laws of Nature, Laws of Freedom, and
the Social Construction of Normativity&rdquo;, <em>Oxford Studies in
Metaethics</em>, 7: 37&ndash;79.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2018a, &ldquo;Nature, Agency, and the
Nature of Agency&rdquo;, <em>Philosophical Inquiries</em>, 6(2):
51&ndash;72.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2018b, &ldquo;Morality, Agency, and Other
People&rdquo;, <em>Ergo: An Open Access Journal of Philosophy</em>, 5:
69&ndash;101.</li>

<li>Wallace, R. Jay, 2012, &ldquo;Constructivism about Normativity:
Some Pitfalls&rdquo;, in Lenman and Shemmer 2012a, pp. 18&ndash;39.
doi:10.1093/acprof:oso/9780199609833.003.0002</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2013, <em>The View from Here: On
Affirmation, Attachment, and the Limits of Regret</em>, New York:
Oxford University Press.</li>

<li>Watkins, Eric and William Fitzpatrick, 2002, &ldquo;O&rsquo;Neill
and Korsgaard on the Construction of Normativity&rdquo;, <em>Journal
